<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="327" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6639390" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6639390" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6639390/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="327" targetBox="[1407,1998,850,1263]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[2021,2617,839,1268]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2022,2198,1084,1109]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">Distribution.</emphasis>
S Gansu, S Shaanxi, Shanxi, NE &amp; SE Sichuan, and S Henan in C China.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="327" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[2021,2617,839,1268]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2023,2303,1200,1229]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 148-232 mm, tail 12-24 mm, ear 16-33 mm,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[1410,2620,1273,1978]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">hindfoot 30-47 mm; weight 112-750 g. Hugh’s Hedgehog is very dark. Dorsal pelage has spines that are smooth and have minute, subterminal, and pale band just before dark tips. Ears are no longer than adjacent spines. Ventral pelage is pale.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="327" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1410,2620,1273,1978]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1411,1523,1392,1425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="327">Habitat.</emphasis>
Semiarid and dry steppe habitats and subalpine and low-elevation coniferous forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
